    {
      "id": "ead970439d51eee14675fee7219f295d0927da08",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-05-30 17:40:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThis is an alternative to http://review.whamcloud.com/10342",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "da3507f5a363f9784080515e3eec20fff4c72e3c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-06-04 18:48:49.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\n(4 comments)\n\nTo be honest, I think switch the position of rename_sanity and lu_object_find is just temporary solution, I think the real problem is that subdir check is not protected by ldlm lock.\n\nIt seems to me that the deadlock described in LU-4725 can be avoided by only checking the direct relationship between src parent and dst parent, i.e. it does not need to use is_subdir, which will go all the way up to root or until remote parent is found.  Instead you can get linkea of src, and just compare the parent FID its dst parent? So\n\n1. global rename lock\n2. Lock the src parent, check whether its parent fid = dst_parent, and sort out the lock order. unlock the src parent.\n3. ldlm lock of all rename objs.\n4. do rename.\n5. unlock objs.\n\nPlease correct me if I miss sth.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "95e075dd1fb4039db5f27b797c48306bdb1a2aff",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 135,
        "name": "Vitaly Fertman",
        "email": "vitaly.fertman@hpe.com",
        "username": "vitaly_fertman"
      },
      "date": "2014-06-04 20:19:33.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(3 comments)\n\n> To be honest, I think switch the position of rename_sanity and lu_object_find\n> is just temporary solution, I think the real problem is that subdir check is not\n> protected by ldlm lock.\n\nwrong. subdir check is only needed to check the hierarchy, which cannot change because we do hold rename global lock. regarding an individual object, it can be destroyed at any time by close of unlinked object, without taking any ldlm lock.\n\n> It seems to me that the deadlock described in LU-4725 can be avoided by \n> only checking the direct relationship between src parent and dst parent, \n> i.e. it does not need to use is_subdir, which will go all the way up to root \n> or until remote parent is found. Instead you can get linkea of src, and just \n> compare the parent FID its dst parent? So\n\nlooks also wrong, you may have several operations, each takes parent-child locks,\neach waits to each other, the last operation is rename which took the bottom child\nand waits for top parent - deadlock.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "7438900086ea8084e02d223314eee3e106fd232b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 135,
        "name": "Vitaly Fertman",
        "email": "vitaly.fertman@hpe.com",
        "username": "vitaly_fertman"
      },
      "date": "2014-06-04 21:24:19.000000000",
      "message": "Uploaded patch set 2.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "86d8e4c7bcec518ca44eaff29e8db7020198d3b0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 12,
        "name": "wangdi",
        "email": "di.wang@intel.com",
        "username": "wangdi",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-06-04 22:52:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nPatch Set 1:\n(3 comments)\n> To be honest, I think switch the position of rename_sanity and lu_object_find > is just temporary solution, I think the real problem is that subdir check is not > protected by ldlm lock.\nwrong. subdir check is only needed to check the hierarchy, which cannot change because we do hold rename global lock. regarding an individual object, it can be destroyed at any time by close of unlinked object, without taking any ldlm lock.\n\nNo, I mean this deadlock, it is because unlink is interleaved with subdir check.\n\n> It seems to me that the deadlock described in LU-4725 can be avoided by > only checking the direct relationship between src parent and dst parent, > i.e. it does not need to use is_subdir, which will go all the way up to root > or until remote parent is found. Instead you can get linkea of src, and just > compare the parent FID its dst parent? So\nlooks also wrong, you may have several operations, each takes parent-child locks, each waits to each other, the last operation is rename which took the bottom child and waits for top parent - deadlock.\n\nHow, only rename can happen like this, but rename is already serialized by global rename lock. If we can rule out src_dir and dst_dir redirect relationship, I think we are fine,  so I do not think you need use is_subdir check here.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
